    55	    "footer_text": "Footer Text",
    56	    "google_analytics_id": "G-XXXXXXXXXX"
    57	}
    58	```
    59	
    60	## Directory Structure
    61	
    62	```
    63	gallerykit/
    64	├── apps/web/                 # Next.js application
    65	│   ├── src/
    66	│   │   ├── app/              # App Router (pages, API routes, server actions)
    67	│   │   ├── components/       # React components
    68	│   │   ├── db/               # Drizzle ORM schema & connection
    69	│   │   ├── lib/              # Utilities (image processing, data layer)
    70	│   │   └── i18n/             # Internationalization config
    71	│   ├── messages/             # Translation files (en.json, ko.json)
    72	│   ├── public/uploads/       # Processed public image derivatives (persistent volume)
    73	│   ├── scripts/              # DB init, migration, seed scripts
    74	│   ├── Dockerfile            # Multi-stage production build
    75	│   └── docker-compose.yml    # Docker deployment config
    76	└── package.json              # Monorepo root (npm workspaces)
    77	```
    78	
    79	## Getting Started
    80	
    81	### Prerequisites
    82	
    83	- **Node.js** v24+
    84	- **npm**
    85	- **MySQL** v8.0+
    86	
    87	### Installation
    88	
    89	```bash
    90	git clone https://github.com/hletrd/gallerykit.git
    91	cd gallerykit
    92	npm install
    93	```
    94	
    95	### Remote Deploy Helper
    96	
    97	To let local automation deploy without re-entering SSH details each run, keep the target SSH config in a gitignored root `.env.deploy` file:
    98	
    99	```bash
   100	cp .env.deploy.example .env.deploy
   101	$EDITOR .env.deploy
   102	npm run deploy
   103	```
   104	
   105	`npm run deploy` now derives the SSH deploy command from `DEPLOY_HOST`, `DEPLOY_USER`, `DEPLOY_KEY`, and `DEPLOY_PATH`. Use `DEPLOY_REMOTE_SCRIPT` if you only need to change the remote entrypoint while keeping the derived SSH wrapper. Keep `DEPLOY_CMD` only as an escape hatch when you need a fully custom command.
   106	
   107	### Environment Setup
   108	
   109	```bash
   110	cp apps/web/.env.local.example apps/web/.env.local
   111	```
   112	
   113	Edit `apps/web/.env.local` with your MySQL credentials, strong admin bootstrap secret, and public URLs:
   114	
   115	```env
   116	DB_HOST=127.0.0.1
   117	DB_PORT=3306
   118	DB_USER=your_user
   119	DB_PASSWORD=your_password
   120	DB_NAME=gallery
   121	ADMIN_PASSWORD=<strong-16+-char-secret-or-argon2-hash>
   122	SESSION_SECRET=<openssl rand -hex 32>
   123	BASE_URL=http://localhost:3000
   124	# Optional: serve uploaded assets from a CDN or reverse proxy prefix
   125	# IMAGE_BASE_URL=https://cdn.example.com
   126	# UPLOAD_MAX_TOTAL_BYTES=2147483648
   127	# TRUST_PROXY=true
   128	```
   129	
   130	If you set `IMAGE_BASE_URL`, do it **before** running `next build` / `docker compose ... --build` so Next.js can allow that remote host for optimized images and CSP.
   131	If you raise `UPLOAD_MAX_TOTAL_BYTES`, make sure your reverse proxy, temp storage, and container memory can safely handle that batch size.
   132	The shipped `apps/web/docker-compose.yml` already forces `TRUST_PROXY=true` and binds the standalone server to `127.0.0.1` when you use the documented host-network + nginx deployment. Keep those protections if you adapt the compose file.
   133	For bootstrap auth, prefer a generated secret or a precomputed Argon2 hash; do not deploy with placeholder passwords such as `password`.
   134	
   135	### Development
   136	
   137	```bash
   138	npm run dev
   139	```
   140	
   141	Opens at [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000).
   142	
   143	### Building
   144	
   145	```bash
   146	npm run build
   147	```
   148	
   149	## Docker Deployment
   150	
   151	1. Configure `apps/web/.env.local`
   152	2. Ensure you are on a Linux host that supports `network_mode: host`, or adapt `apps/web/docker-compose.yml` for your container network.
   153	3. Provide a real `apps/web/src/site-config.json` on the host before starting the compose stack; the checked-in example file is only a template.
   154	4. Run:
   155	
   156	```bash
   157	docker compose -f apps/web/docker-compose.yml up -d --build
   158	```
   159	
   160	The application listens on port 3000 on localhost; publish it through your reverse proxy rather than exposing the host-network process directly. New original uploads are kept in the private data volume, while processed JPEG/WebP/AVIF derivatives remain under `public/uploads/`.
   161	
   162	Legacy originals must not remain under `public/uploads/original/`. The startup path now fails closed in production if that legacy public-original directory still contains files.
   163	
   164	## Tech Stack
   165	
   166	| Layer | Technology |
   167	|-------|-----------|
   168	| Framework | Next.js 16 (App Router) |
   169	| UI | React 19, Tailwind CSS, Radix UI, shadcn/ui |
   170	| Database | MySQL 8.0+, Drizzle ORM |
   171	| Auth | Argon2, HMAC-SHA256 sessions |
   172	| Images | Sharp (parallel AVIF/WebP/JPEG pipeline) |
   173	| i18n | next-intl (en, ko) |
   174	| Deploy | Docker (standalone output) |
   175	
